item.title: The week in 32 photos
Look at me! 30 selfies of the week
Dance between past and present
item.description: Sharp angles, fragmented glass, scaffolding, bright lights, looming robotics -- these elements tower over ghostly, apparition-like people scurrying to and from their destinations.

item.title: I live with my parents and I love it
item.description: I always pictured myself graduating from college, getting a cool job and even having a cute little place of my own.

item.title: Meet the woman with 50 mustaches
item.description: Dallas photographer S. Van Lokey may not be able to grow a bushy mustache of her own, but that hasn't stopped her from taking her own "hairied" Movember journey.

item.title: Celebs to honor the top 10
item.description: CNN's Anderson Cooper will host this year's star-studded "CNN Heroes: An All-Star Tribute," which airs Sunday, December 7, at 8:00 p.m. ET.

item.title: How to vote for Hero of the Year
item.description: CNN's Anderson Cooper explains the voting process for CNN Hero of the Year.

item.title: Think fireballs are rare? Think again
Comet lander conks out, may be dead
item.description: After an improbable 10-year, 310-million-mile journey to become the first ever space vehicle to make a soft landing on a comet, the Philae probe may have ended its mission prematurely.

item.title: 11 other really cool space missions
item.description: It's hard to top the tricky, first-ever landing on a comet, broadcast live on the Internet.

item.title: Was mental illness his only crime?
item.description: Blaec Lammers will spend the prime of his life in prison. His mother believes her son's only crime was being diagnosed with a mental illness.

item.title: Paraplegic groom's first-dance
item.description: Joey Johnson, a paraplegic, surprised his wife on their wedding day with a contraption that let him stand for their first dance.

item.title: 'Walking Dead' in Georgia
item.description: Even a zombie apocalypse has a silver lining.

item.title: Prison hosts Daddy-Daughter dance
item.description: Daughters dressed up in frilly dresses and tights, many of their fathers in suits and ties: It could have been a scene at almost any school's father-daughter dance. But it's not. Prisoners and their daughters dressed up for the first-ever Daddy-Daughter Dance at Miami's federal prison.

item.title: Corvette Nation strikes back
item.description: A special team of hotshot Corvette restorers has dealt a blow against an evil sinkhole that desecrated the National Corvette Museum in Bowling Green, Kentucky.

item.title: Ex-SEAL: I killed bin Laden
item.description: Former Navy SEAL Robert O'Neill said in an interview with The Washington Post that he was the one who fired the final shot to kill Osama bin Laden in 2011.

item.title: Hippo's mystery conception
item.description: Mara had been putting on weight lately, so those around her thought something was up. But she was on birth control, so if there was to be a baby, that would be a bit of a surprise.

item.title: Paisley's 'Black-ish' joke at CMAs
item.description: Brad Paisley has never shied away from controversial topics in his music: Alcohol helps white people dance. Celebrities can act like fools because people think they're cool. Real guys don't get "manicured, waxed and botoxed."

item.title: Dying women teach lesson
item.description: For a brief moment, both women, who were dying of brain cancer, took us away from the negative political ads blasting from our TVs and gave us the most important message of all: to enjoy our time on Earth.

item.title: A first for new Navy jet
item.description: A combination of old and new hooked up off the coast of San Diego Monday to give the U.S. Navy a glimpse into its future.

item.title: Test pilots' workplace
item.description: It's an unforgiving place, 45,000 feet above the Earth. It's brutally cold up there, as low as 59 degrees below zero, and there's so little air to breathe, it takes just seconds to pass out.

item.title: Fliers 'State of Hate' airline survey
item.description: Almost 30,000 travelers filled out a Spirit Airlines survey detailing what passengers really hate about airlines.

item.title: National anthem makes NFL star cry
item.description: Before the final whistle at Monday night's game between the Indianapolis Colts and the New York Giants, trumpeter Chris Botti had already won.

item.title: Magliozzi of NPR's 'Car Talk' dies
item.description: Tom Magliozzi, half of the "Click and Clack" team of brothers who hosted NPR's "Car Talk" radio show, died Monday. He was 77.

item.title: NICU mimics mom's womb
item.description: Doctors and nurses at a specialized unit at CHOC have implemented a system they say is dramatically reducing disability and infection rates among micro preemies.

item.title: Woman in catcall video: 'Not unique'
item.description: What started as an expose of the harassment women face in public has turned into online death and rape threats against the woman in the video.

item.title: 6 most romantic small towns
item.description: For an otherwise entertaining movie, "Gone Girl" had kind of a downer message.

item.title: Dad says sons called 'Ebola'
item.description: Fears over Ebola have made the jump from pundits to the playground.

item.title: School shooting victim forgives
item.description: That's how a 14-year-old high school student, lured to a lunch table, shot in the face and told he can never play football again, feels about his attacker.

item.title: 'Hello Kitty Con' draws 25,000 fans
item.description: The Hello Kitty icon turns 40, drawing 25,000 fans to the first-ever 'Hello Kitty Con.' Just don't say Happy Birthday Kitty. The Japanese firm owning the image says it's an anniversary.

item.title: 'Pumpkinsteins:' They're alive!
item.description: There are heads growing on Tony Dighera's farm, and they're not made of lettuce.

item.title: Agents: The devil made him do it
item.description: Though he told authorities that the devil made him do it, Satanists disapproved, after a man allegedly shattered a stone copy of the Ten Commandments last week.

item.title: Famed explorer's notebook found
item.description: Explorer Robert Falcon Scott died in 1912 while crossing Antarctica, but his story lives on in artifacts that continue to be discovered on the frozen continent at the bottom of the world.

item.title: Berkeley students want no Maher
item.description: TV host Bill Maher started his career as a standup comedian. But students at the University of California, Berkeley aren't laughing at his latest antics; they're petitioning to have him removed as their 2014 fall commencement speaker.

item.title: Girls skip school to join ISIS?
item.description: German authorities intercepted the accused teen trio and put them on a plane back to the U.S., where they were greeted by FBI agents.

item.title: Barkley: Blacks 'brainwashed'
item.description: Charles Barkley hasn't met a sensitive topic he couldn't dig into, and now he's speaking on what he calls a "dirty, dark secret" in the African-American community.

item.title: WWII German U-boat found
item.description: A World War II German U-boat, sunk during the Battle of the Atlantic more than 72 years ago, has been discovered off the coast of North Carolina, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration announces.

item.title: Eleanor Roosevelt's sharp tongue
item.description: "Dammed if you do, damned if you don't" -- 12 inspirational quotes from the U.S. President's charismatic wife.

item.title: How much sex counts as exercise?
item.description: When I think of the ultimate sex workout, I picture the scene from "Mr. and Mrs. Smith" where Brad Pitt and Angelina Jolie throw each other around their kitchen for an hour. Unfortunately, not every sexual experience is quite that... well, high-intensity. But how many calories do we really burn in the act?

item.title: Students took fake 'paper classes'
item.description: For 18 years, thousands of students at the University of North Carolina took fake "paper classes," and advisers funneled athletes into the program to keep them eligible, an independent report finds.

item.title: Oklahoma cold cases solved
item.description: A decades-old mystery that captivated Oklahoma has been solved after officials confirmed the identities of two groups of people -- some of them teens -- who went missing in 1969 and 1970.

item.title: Moon bites sun
item.description: If there's one thing we've learned about the CNN iReport community, it's that you all love to capture celestial events.

item.title: Romance ends in chimney
item.description: The perils of online dating are well-documented. But the mantle of absurdity in dating folklore might now belong to a Los Angeles-area man, and it's for where his online flame turned up -- behind his mantel.

item.title: 12 best meat cities in America
item.description: With the possible exception of smartphone technology, nothing's seen more practical advances this millennium than food.

item.title: Mystery space plane back on Earth
item.description: Whatever it was doing up in space, we may never know, but the U.S. Air Force's unmanned X-37B space plane returned to Earth this week, with still no details from the military on the nearly two-year mission.

item.title: San Fran stations ban Lorde's 'Royals'
item.description: With the World Series on the line, radio stations in San Francisco aren't taking any chances.

item.title: Megaquake could hit West Coast
item.description: It's been 25 years since a massive earthquake rattled San Francisco. Is the West Coast ready for the next big one?

item.title: Clowns scaring residents
item.description: A rash of "creepy clown" sightings in California has left some residents unnerved, and it all appears to have started with the "Wasco Clown."

item.title: Her death linked to latest case?
item.description: As the years wore on after her death, Cassandra Morton's family learned to live without knowing who committed this heinous act. Until now.

item.title: US changes mind on gay marriage
item.description: Stephanie Coontz says 11 years ago only one state allowed same sex marriage. Soon, some 60% of Americans will live where gays can marry. How did attitudes change so quickly?

item.title: Drought victims drink in kindness
item.description: California's historic drought leaves hundreds of homes without running water. Enter a godsend: A grandmother, 71, delivers love by the bottle.

item.title: 'SNL' veteran dies at 57
item.description: Actress and comedian Jan Hooks died in New York on Thursday. Her representative, Lisa Lieberman, confirmed the death to CNN but provided no additional information.

item.title: Did tweet get her kicked off jet?
item.description: Tweeting about why her Tuesday night flight was delayed got Lisa Carter-Knight kicked off a JetBlue airplane, she claims.

item.title: Carter criticizes Obama on ISIS
item.description: Former President Jimmy Carter said President Barack Obama "waited too long" to go after ISIS and criticized what he described as the president's changing foreign policy.

item.title: My right to death with dignity at 29
item.description: On New Year's Day, after months of suffering from debilitating headaches, I learned that I had brain cancer.

item.title: Parents anxious about enterovirus
item.description: When news first broke about a month ago about enterovirus D68, also known as EV-D68, with hundreds of children hospitalized across the United States with respiratory illnesses, I definitely took notice.

item.title: Who are the U.S. Ebola patients?
item.description: As another American patient with Ebola arrives in the United States, here is a look at the American patients who have been diagnosed with this deadly virus.

item.title: A sperm bank just for supersmart
item.description: It sounds like the plot of a Hollywood movie: An eccentric millionaire creates a sperm bank with donations from only extraordinary men -- Nobel laureates, an Olympic athlete and geniuses with off-the-chart IQs.

item.title: 18 annoying things in airports
item.description: Whether they're cutting their fingernails mid-flight or aggressively establishing armrest hegemony, we've already addressed the most irritating things travelers do on airplanes.

item.title: Gender differences at school
item.description: Every so often a boy shows up to school at Garden Oaks Montessori in Houston wearing nail polish or a headband. When that happens, children -- and, sometimes parents -- ask questions.

item.title: Paul Revere dies at 76
item.description: Paul Revere, leader of the 1960s rock band Paul Revere and the Raiders, died Saturday at his home in Idaho, the band's website reported. He was 76.

item.title: Aircraft carrier's 30-ton gift
item.description: The U.S. Navy's oldest nuclear aircraft carrier has given a piece of itself to one the younger carriers in the fleet.

item.title: Man in bubble rescued off coast
item.description: An ultra-marathoner trying to "run" from Florida to Bermuda in a human-powered inflatable bubble was rescued Saturday morning after he signaled for help, the Coast Guard said.

item.title: Ferguson flash mob disrupts symphony
item.description: Rather than take to the streets of Ferguson, these demonstrators took their demands to the seats of the symphony.

item.title: Does he really think voters are stupid?
item.description: MIT economics professor Jonathan Gruber called voters stupid, the GOP is calling him the Obamacare architect, and Democrats are calling it all a misunderstanding.

item.title: Secret memos show FBI obsessed with MLK
item.description: MLK was followed constantly and regularly harassed by the FBI. See the secret FBI memos for yourself.

item.title: Guess who's coming to New York?
item.description: Prince William and his wife, Catherine, will cross the pond to New York for the first time next month, paying their respects to victims at the National September 11 Memorial and Museum in lower Manhattan and catching a Brooklyn Nets game at the Barclays Center.

item.title: Separated at birth, reunited online
item.description: Anais Bordier and Samantha Futerman have the same laugh and the same freckled cheeks. They wear their hair the same way and have since they were babies. They share a hatred of cooked carrots, a love of the same color nail polish and the need to sleep 10 hours a day.

item.title: 1 city; 1,111 sex crimes; 0 investigations?
item.description: Five New Orleans detectives may have failed to investigate 1,111 sex crimes over a 3-year period, a report says.

item.title: FBI's 'suicide letter' to MLK
item.description: Historian Beverly Gage uncovered an "anonymous" FBI letter to Martin Luther King Jr. telling him to "kill himself."

item.title: What weight loss really looks like
item.description: A young man posted a video that show his loose skin and explains his insecurities after extreme weight loss.

item.title: Gas scam nets millions of dollars
item.description: They look like ordinary guys pumping gas. But authorities say they are thieves, using stolen credit cards to fill vehicles fitted with huge hidden tanks. The fuel is resold at cut rates.

item.title: Doctor with Ebola arrives in U.S.
item.description: Dr. Martin Salia, who is a legal permanent resident of the United State, was diagnosed with Ebola in his native Sierra Leone. He's being treated at The Nebraska Medical Center in Omaha.

item.title: 4 workers die in Texas chemical plant leak
item.description: Four workers were killed Saturday after a chemical leak at a DuPont plant in La Porte, Texas, on the outskirts of Houston, plant manager Randall Clements said.

item.title: Report: Michael Brown's fatal encounter lasted less than 2 minutes
item.description: The fatal encounter that ended with the shooting of Michael Brown by officer Darren Wilson was brief, lasting less than two minutes, the St. Louis Post-Dispatch reported.

item.title: U.S. Joint Chiefs chairman goes to Iraq
item.description: Days after refusing to rule out recommending U.S. ground troops in Iraq, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff arrived in the turbulent Middle Eastern nation to talk with officials there about combating ISIS, an official said.

item.title: Jose Canseco claims 'my finger fell off' during poker game
item.description: In tweets, former baseball slugger Jose Canseco says the finger he'd accidentally shot partly fell off while he was playing poker.

item.title: Frats suspended after freshman dies
item.description: The death of a West Virginia University student who was found unconscious at a fraternity house has prompted officials to suspend all Greek activities on campus.
